            <pb n="1"/> 
            
            <p>Jews&#39; College&#44;<lb/>
                10&#44; Finsbury Square&#44;<lb/>
                London&#44; E. C.  18<lb/></p>
            <p>The subjects taught in the Jews&#39; College<lb/> are&#58;<lb/></p>
            <p>I Religious subjects.<lb/></p>
            <p>1. &#91;Hebrew&#93; &#40;6 hours weekly&#41; with &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/>
                the first year &#91;Hebrew&#93;	This is the present<lb/>
                &#45;&#45;2nd&#45;&#45;&#91;Hebrew&#93;		course&#59; another order<lb/>
                &#45;&#45;3rd&#45;&#45;&#91;Hebrew&#93;		might perhaps follow.<lb/>
                &#45;&#45;4th&#45;&#45;&#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/>
                2 &#91;Hebrew&#93; &#40;2 h.&#41; &#91;Hebrew&#93;; besides before every<lb/> festival &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/>
                3&#41; &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; &#40;1 h.&#41; especially &#91;Hebrew&#93;.<lb/>
                4. &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; sometimes with<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93; &#40;2 h&#41;<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93;.<lb/>
                the historical books are read in the Bible<lb/> Hist. lesson&#44; the rest is expected to be read<lb/> privately by the pupils&#59; now and then<lb/> they are examined about it.<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>5&#41; Biblical and Postbiblical History<lb/> &#40;1 h&#41; divided into 4 parts for the 4<lb/> years.<lb/>
                6&#41; &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/>
                7&#41; Seminar and exercises in translating<lb/> from English into Hebrew.<lb/></p>
            <p>II Secular subjects.<lb/></p>
            <p>The students of the Jews&#39; College are<lb/> prepared for the examinations of<lb/> the London University&#59; classics<lb/> and Mathematics are taught<lb/> accordingly.<lb/>
                NB. Singing Chat has been taught hitherto<lb/> only for the purpose of the &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; will now<lb/> be introduced for Coll. and School together<lb/> to be taught generally and systematically.<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>The students attend the College daily<lb/> &#40;except &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#41;.  Sunday and Friday<lb/> from 9&#45;1 o&#39;clock the other days<lb/> from 9&#45;1 and 2&#45;5.<lb/>
                Every &#91;Hebrew&#93; morning there is Divine<lb/> Service in the College&#44; in order that<lb/> the students might have every possibility<lb/> for practicing the reading of the Prayers<lb/> and the Thorah.<lb/>
                There is a school &#40;4 Classes&#41; connected<lb/> with the College for two purposes.<lb/>
                1&#41; that boys desiring to enter the<lb/> College be properly prepared and provided<lb/> with the required elementary knowledge.<lb/>
                2&#41; that College students have practice<lb/> in teaching.<lb/>
                This school is at present attended by<lb/> about 60 pupils.<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>The Standard for the first &#40;highest&#41; Class<lb/> is&#58; 1&#41; Religious subjects<lb/> the &#91;Hebrew&#93; with the &#91;Hebrew&#93; every week&#44; and<lb/> 1 hr at least till &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> before the festivals &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  Bibl. and Postbibl. Hist.<lb/> longer times about various parts of<lb/> Religion and Bibl. Hist.<lb/> Hebrew exercises.<lb/>
                2&#41; secular subjects.<lb/>  The standard for the first class is<lb/> the same as for the Oxford and Cambridge<lb/> Middle Class Examinations.<lb/></p>
            
